    <div align="left" id="post_message_387508">Fharisa groaned softly as she settled her gravid form on a fallen log beside the path. She looked up to see her husband, Lelwhyn, stop and smile tenderly back at her. They had met five years before when they, and several other Wood Elves, had answered the call for guardians and explorers at the elfin outpost of Fironia Vie. They were both skilled rangers and their love for each other had grown swiftly. Now she wanted to have their first child in their homeland of Kelethin.<br />
    Lelwhyn had argued against the journey considering it’s length and her advancing pregnancy. She had said that she would rather have the baby on the road under the familiar and friendly trees of the Faydark forest then on the dangerous continent of Kunark. Because he loved herhe had finally agreed.<br />
    Their ship docked on the continent of Feydwer just days ahead of a brutal storm off The Ocean of Tears. The bad weather forced them to delay their journey and shelter in the dwarven city of Kaladim. They had stayed with the Dwarves for two weeks as they waited for the roads and passes thru Butcherblok Mountains to become fit for travel. <br />
    During their stay with the Dwarves they had heard many rumors that the Orcs of Clan Crushbone were acting up again. Some said the stupid, evil beasts were gearing up for war. Others thought that something had the Orcs running scared. All the rumors had one thing in common though. Every Dwarf would raise his, or her, ale mug high and insist that if they and a few of their friends went to Faydark, they would solve the Orc problem permanently.<br />
    Now just three days, at a steady waddle, out from Kelethin Fharisa was beginning to relax. She knew Lelwhyn was worried about the Orcs and was trying to get them safely to the tree city as quickly as possible. But she felt safe under his watchful eye. There wasn’t an Orc alive that could get within bowshot of the two alert rangers. And Lelwhyn’s skill with a sword had kept them both alive against much fiercer beasts then Orcs.<br />
    So it was with complete amazement that she watched the shadow detach it’s self from the tree just behind Lelwhyn. Part of the shadow seemed to drape over his shoulder and he arched backwards. She saw the Elf she loved open his mouth, but a fountain of blood drowned out any cry he might have made. She watched in stunned horror as the shadow let the limp form fall to the ground and stepped forward.<br />
    Amalice Sa’Dath stepped over the body, every nerve still tingling from the feel of the last heart beat of the fallen Elf thrumming along the length of the blade he had buried in his back. He is Teir’Dal, a Dark Elf. Mortal enemies of the light skinned Elves of Feydwer, and all the goodly races for that matter. Most of his dark hearted brothers and sisters considered nothing but their hatred of the light lovers when they made a kill. The dark teachings of the god Innoruuk left no room for pleasure. Amalice truly enjoyed his kills. A strike so swift the victim never knew what hit them, or the fear in their eyes as he stalked prey that he himself had warned ahead of time. Amalice enjoyed the hunt as much as the kill. He smiled congenially at the stunned Elfin woman.<br />
    “Calmly now Elf.” He said soothingly,”I’m here for slaves. And in you I see two for the price of one.”<br />
    His voice shook Fharisa enough to tear her eyes from Lelwhyn’s body. She found herself mesmerized by his face. His eyes held an amused twinkle. And his smile, though she could tell came easily and often to his face, was cold as death. Fear like she had never known held her motionless as he came slowly closer. She saw his empty hands held out before him, the lopsided frown as he looked down at her. He made slight beckoning motions with his hands. Slowly, almost as if moving against her will, Fharisa placed her hands in his. Gently he raised her to her feet, his eyes seemed to study her.<br />
    “Yes,” he said,” you will make a most interesting little plaything in time.”<br />
    Fharisa felt a small surge of hope as she saw the fires of lust light the eyes of the Dark Elf. If she could use this beasts passions against him, maybe she would get a chance to escape. Or better yet a chance to kill the evil thing that had destroyed her family to be.<br />
    Smiling wickedly he brought her hands up as if to kiss them. Then he noticed the ring on her finger. Gently entwining the fingers of both her hands in one of his. He began to trace his finger around the ring she wore.<br />
    “More then just pleasure I take it. Oh, what is the word you silly fools use? Husband, yes that’s it.” He shook his head disapprovingly, “Why anyone would limit themselves to just one for life is beyond my understanding.”<br />
    Unexpected pain buckled her knees. Fharisa found herself being held up by the surprisingly strong grip of the Dark Elf. A ripping pain floods her body as he holds something up for her to see.<br />
    “A son.” He says with amusement as she recognizes what it is. “ I bet he would have been proud.”<br />
    Amalice watches the pain and horror play across her face avidly. The hopelessness that fills her eyes thrilling him to the core. Her guttural sounds, more animal then elfin are music to his dark ears. Slowly he lets her fingers slip thru his, deftly removing her ring as he does. He holds it up admiring the workmanship. His senses tingling from the magic it most surely holds. <br />
    The snapping of branches behind him breaks his moment of pleasure, and he tenses himself up for action.<br />
    “I thought you said you were going to let her live?”<br />
    Anger he couldn’t hide crept thru Amalice’s voice.”I thought I told YOU to stay back until I called you Human!”<br />
    “I’m hungry,” the young man replied defensively, “I came to see if they have any food in those packs.”<br />
    “Food?” Amalice growled.”You said you could cook?” He throws the small bloody body he still holds at the young man. “Here cook that. I go to wash the stench of this vermin from me. Have the camp set and...dinner ready when I get back Human.”<br />
   “I have a name besides Human!” the young man called after him.<br />
   “None that I care about.” Amalice shot back scathingly as he stormed off into the trees.<br />
  <br />
    “My compliments to the chef.” Amalice said as he tossed a small bone into the fire, wiped his hands and pulled the ring from his pocket to examine it in the fire light later that night.<br />
    “Is it magic?” Asked the young Human across the fire from him.<br />
    “Yes.” He answered absently. Not really paying all that much attention.<br />
    “Then I want it.”<br />
    Amalice raised an eyebrow and slowly looked at the young man as if for the first time. He had found the young shadow knight wounded and in combat with two of the Crushbone Orcs just a few days ago. He was hard pressed and desperately trying to call upon the magical powers granted him by his god Cazic Thule. Amalice had slain one of the Orcs with a well placed backstab, that the fool Orc never even saw coming. In the moment of surprise and hesitation that over came the second Orc at it’s companions fall the young shadow knight had crushed it’s head with his mace. There had been no mercy or compassion in Amalice’s rescue of this Human. The Orcs had refused to sell him the slaves he had come to this land for. Such an insult could not be tolerated. Now he was trying any way he could to make them suffer for their choice. Amalice had killed many Orcs and almost as many Elves. Always leaving Orcish weapons or even Orc bodies to make it look like an Orc attack. The supposed Orcish uprising had brought many mercenaries such as this young Human looking to make some money or a name for themselves.<br />
    “Consider it payment for this meal and all the work I’ve been doing for you these past days.” The young man added reasonably.<br />
    A long silence grew between them, and the young man moved his hand slowly closer to the battered and rusty mace sitting next to him.<br />
    Finely Amalice shrugged and flipped the ring high into the air.<br />
    “Here. It’s yours then.” he said.<br />
    Instantly the mans hands shot forward and out as he strained to trace the path of the ring thru the air. Too easy was Amalice’s only thought as he throw a dagger at the exposed throat. Sinking it deeply in the soft skin under his chin. A look of surprise and betrayal flashed across the young face as he fell backward drowning in his own blood. Amalice caught the ring as it fell and said to the dying man.<br />
    “Greed is a vary fine line to walk. Too little and you never get what you want, but too much can get you dead.”<br />
    Amalice returned to his contemplation of the ring, paying no more attention to the last feeble movements on the other side of the fire. He knew many lovely Teir’Dal women back home. All he had to do was figure out where such a gift would do him the most good.<br />
<br />
<br />
Amalice Sa'Dath<br />
Grandmaster Assassin<br />
Tunare server<br />
Gale of Destruction</div>
